8 Support Poll Results That Show Donald Trump Is Serious
Some have tried to brand him as a wind vane.
Others think he's just a joke.
Some are waiting to collapse.
While some Republicans have tried to get Donald Trump out of the top spot in support polls, it has not (yet) succeeded.
Of the last 11 national polls in ten, Donald Trump has been in charge of a double-digit number, and some have begun to seriously consider what this means for the real estate king's nomination prospects.
Of course, the election period is only in the early stages.
These results do not yet mean that Trump is likely to become a Republican candidate.
Commentators point out that at this point in 2011, Rick Perry was losing his lead to rising Herman Cain, neither of whom got behind any states in the nomination process.
There are also many reasons why he would have problems in the general election.
However, outside groups, such as Jeb Bush's Super PAC and the conservative economic organization Club for Growth, have noted Trump's persistence and have begun to use his funds to overthrow him.
The following recent support poll results suggest that the real estate king is not just a passing phase:
Trump's popularity figures have made a turnaround.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, support polls from Monmouth University showed that only two out of ten Republicans welcomed the real estate king.
By mid-July, the figure was 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, the figure was 52 per cent.
Currently, six out of ten Republicans welcome Donald Trump.
About three out of ten say they are negative.
These figures are also true in the first primary states.
In a poll conducted by Quinnipiac University in Iowa last week, 60 percent of Republicans said they welcomed Trump.
Two-thirds of Republican voters would be happy if Trump became a candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would be either "enthusiastic" or "satisfied" if Trump were a candidate.
Only two in ten said they would be "shocked" if he became a candidate.
Only Ben Carson achieves roughly the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43% "enthusiastic" vs. Trump's 40%).
The Next Most Exciting?
Marco Rubio at only 21%.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters would be "unsatisfied" or "shocked" if Jeb Bush, a favorite of those in power, became a candidate.
Trump's fiery nature is not a problem for most Republicans.
