According to Quinnipiac's poll last week, the number in Iowa, which hosts the first party convention, is the same: 52% of Republicans think that Trump has the right temperament for a leader.
However, according to an ABC/Post poll, 44 percent think his character isn't appropriate for being president, and nearly six out of ten feel his character doesn't belong in the White House.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When Republican voters think like commentators, they think Trump is a real option.
According to a CNN/ORC poll, four out of ten people said Trump was the most likely candidate to be nominated by Republicans.
At the end of July, four out of ten supported Jeb Bush.
Disclosure: Republican Party voters have not always had access to the brightest crystal ball possible.
At this time in the last legislature, four out of ten Republicans felt that Rick Perry would be nominated, with only 28 percent supporting the final candidate, Mitt Romney.
In any case, this shows that the majority of Republican Party voters find the Trump campaign credible.
Even if Republicans sided with another candidate, Trump would still win almost everyone.
Some commentators have pointed out that the fragmented field is likely to have contributed to Trump's leadership, as anti-Trump support is divided among numerous other candidates.
