Jeremy Corbyn's First Appearance in Prime Minister's Question Time
Corbyn's first appearance in Question Time has been eagerly awaited since his election
Jeremy Corbyn, the new Labour leader, meets David Cameron for the first time in Prime Minister's Question Time.
Corbyn rises to ask the first of his six questions shortly after noon, and is likely to be closely watched by both the media and Labour MPs for his performance.
Corbyn has called for "less theatre and more facts" for this weekly show.
He has also said that he could leave some of the opportunities to his colleagues.
This encounter is the first parliamentary test of Corbyn's leadership since he was appointed to the shadow government and spoke at the annual meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand quietly during the national anthem at Tuesday's memorial service, which was held on the 75th anniversary of the Battle for Britain air war, has attracted criticism among Conservative MPs and appeared in several front-page stories.
Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
Corbyn's spokesman said he "stands respectfully silent" and that he recognizes "the bravery of the Royal Air Force in the Great Britain Air War."
A member of Corbyn's shadow government, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight programme that he would have urged the Labour leader to sing the national anthem despite his belief that the royal house should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to be involved in Corbyn's inner circle, citing disagreements over economic, defense and foreign affairs, initially supported by less than a sixth of the parliamentary party as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says that policy differences regarding the party's position in the European Union, as well as the government's subsidy cap, have also "accumulated" within the Labour Party since Corbyn's appointment.
Corbyn said at a meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions that the Labour Party is proposing an amendment that would remove the entire roof.
Hours later, the shadow government's Secretary of Labor and Pensions, Smith, stated that the party was "quite clear" about their only opposition to the government's plans to lower the ceiling from £26,000 to £23,000.
Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader David Cameron has faced in the past decade to be the leader of the Conservative Party.
The Labour leader has promised a new approach to politics and now says he has "massed" ideas into questions for the Prime Minister, and received more than 30,000 proposals.
Islington North MP Corbyn has said that the nature of the Prime Minister's Question Hours is too confrontational and that he intends to refrain from both witty words and snarling, promising instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Corbyn has said that the shadow government's financial secretary, Angela Eagle, will be his substitute during Question Time when Corbyn is not attending - for example when Cameron is abroad.
Corbyn has also suggested that other colleagues could also be allowed to speak at times, and he has said that he has approached the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, about the matter.
When Cameron took the lead in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the kind of political theater that is often associated with Prime Minister's Question Time, but he later had to admit his failure.
Since they began to be televised in 1990, the Prime Minister's Question Time has been an important gauge in assessing the leader's discretion, his control of the House of Commons, and his position among other MPs, although critics have criticized Question Hours for becoming just a travesty that calls for far-reaching reforms.
