Metcash launches grassroots campaign against Aldi infiltration
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from the Aldi attack in southern and western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grassroots campaign to defend the market share of IGA traders in southern and western Australia prior to Aldi's $700 million attack.
Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first store early next year in South and Western Australia, with up to 120 stores to come. Meanwhile, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food retailers and building the IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing, as well as events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA retailers and suppliers have jumped in, and brands such as Simmo's, an ice cream maker from Dunsborough, offer samples at IGA stores, and store owners sell discounted tickets to Australian football matches to their regulars.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details about its defense strategy on September 29 as this food, alcohol and hardware wholesaler organizes an annual investor strategy day.
There is a lot at stake, with South and West Australia making up nearly 30% of the IGA stores in Metcash combined, with higher margins of return than the IGA network in the eastern states of Metcash.
South and West Australian shoppers are known to be parochial, with IGA dealers having a much larger market share than New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland: over 30% in the south and 24% in the west compared to 14% in the eastern states.
Analysts such as Morgan Stanley, however, believe that Aldi will capture about 5 percent of the food market in the two states within 12 months of opening its first stores.
In a report this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA dealers could lose $360 million annually in sales and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in the south and 30 in the west next year, generating revenues of $500 and $600 million in these areas.
Loss of food and food sales and quantities at Metcash's high fixed cost base could cost Metcash about $13 million in operating profit losses before interest and taxes, Kierath said.
Meanwhile, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Ald and Coles, although a recent Roy Morgan study found that IGA customers were the most loyal of all.
Morgan Stanley believes that Metcash's food and food sales will fall by 3.8% in 2016; 4.1% in 2017 and 2.1% in 2018, so that its market share will fall from 14% in 2015 to 10.3% in 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, a manager of a leading investment fund and founder of Magellan Financial Group, said at a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash could "very possibly disappear in a decade."
Metcash has declined to respond publicly to Douglass' comments.
However, it is understood that a member of Metcash's board of directors had contacted Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has fallen from 18% to 14% since 2010, and revenues from Metcash's food and food business, which distributes products to approximately 1,200 IGA dealers, have fallen by 43% since 2012, indicating a reduction in debt financing for operations when sales and margins are under pressure.
However, the wholesaler stands its ground, and has invested more than $150 million annually in lowering the prices of hundreds of products each week to the same level as Coles and Woolworths, helping IGA dealers renovate stores by adding faster-growing fresh food, and bringing a better range of private label products to market.
Metcash CEO Ian Morrice says that lowering prices and improving stores have increased appeal, and he hopes the wholesaler will return to the path of revenue growth in 2017, for the first time in four years.
Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy supports Thanasi Kokkinakis
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves honor rather than criticism for his conduct
Thanasi Kokkinakis has had to suffer as a bystander in a recent storm that has raged around his friend Nick Kyrgios, who deserves credit rather than criticism for his own conduct, says Steve Healy, president of the Australian Tennis Federation.
A younger member of the talented duo known as "Special Ks" Kokkinakis was unwittingly made public about the incident in which Kyrgios annoyed Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
Shortly after, in a fiery qualifier match in Cincinnati, the Chief Justice had to twice separate Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison when Harrison declared, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten that brat."
Although Kokkinakis was last seen breaking his bat after a cramp ruined his potential win over Richard Gasquet at the US Open, Healy has been a staunch defender of Kokkinakis.
Right now, the young man is in Glasgow competing with Sam Groth for another spot in the doubles with Bernard Tomic in the semi-finals of the Davis Cup against Britain.
"I'm pretty strongly of the opinion that Thanasi has just been dragged into the brawl," Healy said.
He broke his bat when he lost for a cramp at the US Open, but he's not the first player to break his bat when he's frustrated, and I know Thanas well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But he has behaved extremely well, even in rather provocative situations at the US Open with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves praise.
He's got a great team around him, he's got a great family around him, and I think he's been treated a little harshly.
He is very mature by the age of 19, he works hard, fits in with the team and so on, and has never had any problems with other players. He is appreciated in the dressing room, he trains hard, is in good shape and is quite a calm and mature young man, and I think he should be judged according to his merits.
Healy has also supported the decision not to include Kyrgios in the important games starting on Friday, describing this "joint decision" as a good solution for everyone, but still supporting the Canberra player's return to the team's regulars.
"We want the team to be completely focused on the games and not all the controversy around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
