Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method may one day replace deep brain stimulation. It is an invasive procedure in which people's brains are led to electrical impulses to treat Parkinson's disease.
Shuttle pods do not normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when they were surrounded by liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles amplified ultrasonic waves, which then travel inside the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect the TRP-4 ion channels, structures found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report published in the journal Nature Communications.
To make ultrasonically-guided nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motion neurons have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani used ultrasound for modified worms, the microbubbles amplified the sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they turn on the modified motion neurons.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenetics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike light that needs to be sent along an optical fiber to a desired location inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasonic waves can pass through tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that using gene therapy and a therapeutic virus may make it possible for targeted human neurons to momentarily respond to an ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
