Juha Kannelmaa, Superintendent of the Finnish Immigration Service, explains what the situation is in Finland and how it has changed.
Is it the same in Finland?
How many of the applicants disappear "under country" per year?- In 2013, a total of 156 asylum applications for unaccompanied minors were made in Finland.
9 of them disappeared.
In 2014, 196 similar applications were made and 11 of them disappeared, Kannelmaa says.
The reason for the disappearance may be that it becomes clear that the applicant has already been registered in another country applying the Dublin Regulation and may have been found to be of age there.
In this case, it may be more tempting for the applicant to disappear than to continue processing the matter in Finland and be returned to the country responsible for processing the application.
Similarly, some of the missing persons will also be found later when they apply for asylum in another member state.
In 2014, there were a total of 3,651 asylum seekers in Finland, of whom 134 applications were subject to a decision of lapse due to the fact that the applicant had probably moved out of Finland, so 123 adult asylum seekers disappeared during the past year, he says.
Is the number increasing?
As of 6 September this year, we have received a total of 586 asylum applications from minors who came alone.
Overall statistics on missing minor asylum seekers are not yet available this year, but the number of underage applicants is therefore known and has clearly increased, which is likely to affect the number of missing persons as well.
What about those who have received a decision to convert?
Are they also disappearing into the "dark labour market", for example?
This is difficult to assess from the Finnish Immigration Service, as the police are responsible for the implementation of the decisions on proselytism, Kannelmaa emphasises.
