The ECB forecasts an average inflation rate of 0.1% for the euro area this year.
Next year, the rise will pick up to 1.1%, the central bank predicts in its new inflation forecasts announced at the beginning of September.
US Fed next to try to tighten monetary policy
The U.S.'s next recession will start at its fastest in less than a year, but more likely within three years after the country's central bank, the Fed, starts raising interest rates again for a long time.
And in the financial markets, the decline in turn begins before the next recession.
The Fed has hinted that it may start raising interest rates as early as this week and by the end of the year at the latest.
Thus, the next recession could hit at its fastest by next autumn and as a financial market price shock before that.
Or at least that's what happens if the world's largest economy and financial markets work the way they used to - and if they react to the Fed's extortion of the money taps the way they used to.
Such conclusions have been reached by German bank Deutsche Bank's London Market Research strategists Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker in their extensive study of long-term market and economic cycles.
The bank distributed a more than 60-page Long-Term Asset Return Study to its major international customers last week.
The strategists who produced the study and report do not pretend to know exactly when the Fed will start raising interest rates or what will happen in the economy and the market afterwards.
Instead, they use the cool facts and calculations of economic statistics to show how the economy and markets have behaved in the past during and after the Fed rate hikes.
In addition to historical observations, they look at which key variables in the economy and financial markets are now on the same or a different model than at the time of previous interest rate hikes - and what the consequences might be.
It becomes clear that both the economy and the financial markets are now in a more shaky condition to withstand rising interest rates than at any time since the 1950s.
The beginning of the recession may not even be a year
The leaders, who decide on the Fed's monetary policy and its respective tuning, have been hinting all through the summer and early autumn that the time is ripe for interest rates to be raised.
The first interest rate hike in more than nine years may occur as early as this week.
The matter will be resolved during Wednesday and Thursday when the so-called Open Market Committee of the Fed Board meets to decide on the matter at its two-day meeting.
The last time the Fed raised its so-called Fed funds policy rate was in June 2006.
At that time, a series of relatively regular but small interest rate increases of 0.25 percentage points, from 1.25% to 5.25%, ended exactly two years ago.
The symptoms of financial markets began in 2007 with the difficulties of the most risky housing financing in the United States, and a year later the financial crisis tore into a global doomsday nightmare.
The Great Recession came in 2009.
Last time, severe adversity in the financial markets and the real economy began at a slower pace than has typically occurred since previous Fed rate hikes.
Similarly, the trials were then tougher and more severe than at any time since the depression of the 1930s.
Deutsche's strategists have been sifting through the ups and downs of the world's largest economies and financial market reversals since 1950 and in some places since the early 19th century.
They report on the Fed's interest rate increases and their economic and financial impact since the 1950s.
The fastest time since the first rate hike has been less than a year, most often less than three years, and on average less than three and a half years.
The rise in the financial markets has ended within one to two years of the start of the Fed's rate hikes.
The Fed has successively raised and lowered its key interest rate since the early 1950s by a dozen cycles of varying lengths.
Each time has deviated in some respects from the others, and the multiplier is relatively sparse in the review, so it is unlikely to make any definite conclusions about the effects of the next rate hikes.
As the strategy points out, this time a lot is different.
And not just better.
Interest rates too low for too long
The decisive causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, may not be undisputedly discovered even by decades of research.
But three things about the causes that led to the crisis and increased its destructive power are somewhat undisputedly clear:
1) In the 21st century, the Fed, the ECB of the euro area and other major central banks of the world kept their key interest rates too low for too long.
They patched up the traces of the techno bubble, while growing the next one.
2) The amount of debt accumulated over the decades in different parts of the financial and real economy, and already too high, became even larger as a result of the excessive monetary policy of central banks.
It was the largest debt bubble in economic history to date.
3) In most areas of financial markets, the crazily cheap debt financing, which was almost contained in the financial economy in particular, inflated the largest price bubbles in economic history to date, from shares to real estate, bonds and commodities.
Even so, there is hardly much dispute that the financial markets, which had risen to ever more complex levels of leverage, were in an unusually dangerous and volatile state when the Fed and other central banks last pushed up interest rates.
Financial structures based on debt levers, let alone valuation bubbles, lasted no longer than their time after interest rate hikes had begun and the cost of debt financing had turned up.
The risks materialized as a financial crisis followed by a major recession.
Larger bubble and more debt
Deutsche strategists do not guess what will happen next, but give an idea by mentioning things such as:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now kept their monetary policy stance even lighter for even longer than before the financial crisis.
If interest rates were too low for too long before the crisis, they have now been even lower for even longer.
2) For a long time, debt has not been as cheap as it was ten years ago, but now debt money is literally cheaper than free.
Thus, the debt load of the financial and real economy has not eased, but now, in different parts of the economy, there is a heavier debt load than before the financial crisis or half of it ever before.
3) Liquidity from central banks, which has become more frequent and cheaper, has mostly remained in the financial markets and has pushed key asset and security classes to their most expensive levels since the peak before the financial crisis or ever.
Not only do strategists lax the mood with warning signs from the financial markets, but they also point out that not even the U.S. economy has yet recovered from the financial crisis and decades of the heaviest recession to the pattern it has seen in the past.
The Eurozone economy has barely recovered at all.
In other words, the real economy is in an unusually weak condition, but correspondingly, the pressures and risks in the financial markets are incomparably greater than before the financial crisis, when the Fed next begins to tighten its money taps more tightly.
Perhaps the future image of Albert Edwards, a strategist at the French bank Societe Generale, is not as strange as it may seem.
He has for some time coached the bank's international investor clients in the following turnarounds of the Fed:
First the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles burst, and soon it's time for the Fed to rush out the financial fires with even bigger QE money syringes.
