U.S. central bank policymakers are sitting around a huge mahogany table for two days this week at a long-awaited meeting to decide if it is time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At the other end of the central bank's decorative, two-story meeting room is a mural from the United States.
The map is a reminder that the president of the central bank, Janet L. Yellen, and her colleagues should put the nation's financial interests above everything else.
Congress has laid two kinds of responsibility on the shoulders of the central bank: they must maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
However, since the Great Depression, central bankers have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
It is this third requirement that may be the deciding factor in the decision to be announced on Thursday, which is so tight that it cannot even be predicted. The decision on whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the record-breaking incentive brought about by the near-zero short-term interest rate level since late 2008.
While most of the data shows a steady growth in the economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made already-precarious central bank officials even more spooky when it comes to increasing volatility. There is a fear of what would be the impact if the federal funds rate reference value were to be raised by at least a percentage point per quarter.
"Understandably, the labor market and inflation are the first and most important issues to be monitored," says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief financial expert at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I believe that if they are looking for justification for maintaining interest rates, the increased uncertainty in the global market is a valid enough reason to wait yet," he says.
No agreement has been reached on the Central Bank's decision, which, too, creates nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent study by Bloomberg, about half of financial experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
Financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the drawdown, as the key indicator indicates that the potential for growth is only about 30%.
This refers to a decline in the securities market if the central bank increases the level, unless the decision-makers then manage to soften the blow by promising that the next drawdown will not happen in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, to a new figure of 16,599.85.
The recovery was brought about by the expectation that the central bank would keep the level unchanged this week, says John Lonski, chief economics expert for Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It's surprising if the central bank is raising interest rates right now," he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, "they'll have to put a lot of effort into their policy to support the financial markets so they don't panic."
Other experts argue that an elevated level would calm the financial markets as it would eliminate uncertainty about when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it appeared that the central bank would this month be raising interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year, despite the fact that liberals are demanding more economic development in their complaints.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest figure in seven years and close to what the central bank considers the limit for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of picking up.
Although inflation is still below the central bank's 2% annual target, central bank policymakers say the main reason for this is the temporary impact of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "survives higher interest rates and also needs them given the tight labour market situation," says Ian Shepherdson, chief economics expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell by as much as 16 percent from its May record, as investors feared China's slowing economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now nearly 10 percent below its peak in May.
For central bank decision-makers, market turmoil is an additional factor in a complex equation that tells when interest rates should be raised.
"Without these financial market events and recent weeks of coverage of China's economic weakness, policymakers would tighten the level at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
He now predicts that policymakers will wait at least a month to get a better idea of the impact.
"The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still quite unclear and they have little information at their disposal as to the consequences of the events in China," Oliner said.
The welfare of the international economy is not the central bank's main concern, so in principle it should not affect decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Central Bank has become the monetary authority of the world.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been immense.
In 2013, the then president, Ben S. Bernanke, hinted that the central bank could "tighten" the increase in the amount of money, causing upheavals in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interwoven, central bank officials are expected not only to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank's decision-making process is "more art than science," states Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at asset management company Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, remarked this month that "the central bank has in the past overreacted to financial market movements that seem to be separate from the fundamentals of the economy."
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for an increase in interest rates, and Lacker, a voting member of the committee, cites the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points over three meetings "despite its limited, identifiable impact on U.S. economic growth," says Lacker.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should only prioritize financial stability during the Great Crisis, as Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate-setting committee, said in a statement.
The latest turmoil comes nowhere near its level, Posen says.
"Nobody wants to be in a situation where there is a fear of raising interest rates because the market is upset," says Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and does not mention financial stability; as long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
