Twenty police officers and five civilians were injured, he said.
It was not immediately clear why rubber bullets, which are known to have killed but are traditionally used as a less dangerous alternative, appeared to have caused so many deaths.
The clash was the latest in weeks of violent protests across the southern plains of Nepal, where members of an ethnic group called Madhesi say that the new provinces established under the proposed new constitution will undermine their political influence.
There have also been protests in western Nepal as the Tharus group calls for a state of its own.
Since August 10, at least 40 people have been killed in violent clashes, including 11 police officers.
At that time, the four main parties signed an agreement dividing the country into provinces - this is a big step towards a new constitution, but a very controversial issue in Nepal, which has had a central government for centuries.
A new constitution has been planned since 2008, but lawmakers accelerated the process after the devastating earthquake in April killed thousands of people.
Lawmakers have voted this week on the constitutional draft clauses in Kathmandu, and officials have said the new charter could be approved by Sunday.
