Weight-loss surgery may help mildly obese diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight loss surgery than those treated in other ways than surgery.
"It takes a long time to get the mortality data," Dr. Robin Blackstone states. He is a weight loss surgery expert who wrote an editorial for a new study in JAMA Surgery.
For weight loss, or bariatric surgery, different methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but the majority of people surveyed have been morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
A BMI, or weight-to-length ratio, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If a BMI is above 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if a person's BMI is above 30, they are considered to be obese.
You can calculate your own BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery, and gastric reduction, to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of cut individuals fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of people treated by means other than surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
Of those who were operated on, 36% had a complete and 28% partial improvement in diabetes.
By comparison, in the medically treated group, diabetes improved completely by only 1% and partially by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, as well as the "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgery group," the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored patients' blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect blood sugar levels over the long term.
Hemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers write.
Hemoglobin A1c levels after surgery dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
In the medical treatment group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
However, this improved "glycemic control" described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels did not reduce mortality over a five-year period, says lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the mean results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, when compared to the group undergoing gastric reduction surgery, the group undergoing gastric bypass surgery had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), lowered their BMI more (7.4 and 5.1), lowered their hemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 percent and 2.1 percent respectively), and was more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission (46.9 percent and 16.7 percent respectively).
Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenixin says that while the study does not show survival or surgery after five years, there are research results from Sweden where surgery led to longer lives in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people undergoing weight-loss surgery had a 29% lower chance of dying over a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study shows no improvement in the survival of surgical patients, Blackstone says the results are encouraging for individuals with a BMI less than 35 who are interested in surgery.
"Research results are crucial precisely in showing that surgery is safe for the lower BMI group," and is not associated with an increased risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take their weight very seriously when the patient's BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we'll wait too long before we take this seriously," he says.
I believe that once a person has amassed these genetic changes that permanently prepare their body for obesity and diabetes, it is very difficult to reverse the situation.
