Glencore raises $2.5 billion in stock sales
Swiss-based mining giant Glencore, which suffered a crash in commodity prices, raised $2.5 billion on Wednesday by selling shares as part of its extensive debt-cutting plan.
Glencore, listed on the London Stock Exchange, reported in a notification that it had sold new shares worth approximately £1.6 billion to reduce its debt.
The company, which lost 57% of its market value this year, is struggling with plummeting commodity prices as China's slowdown puts a strain on demand and wreaks havoc on all markets.
The new entry raised the value of Glencore shares to the top of the London Stock Exchange in Wednesday's morning trades.
Shares rose 2.77 percent to 131.60 pence in the FTSE 100 index, which opened 0.69% higher.
Glencore had disclosed a $2.5 billion stock deal the previous week as part of its broader plan to cut its $30 billion debt burden by about a third.
The company sold new share capital for 125 pence a share, which meant a 2.4% reduction in Tuesday's closing price.
The company sold 1.3 billion shares worth a total of 9.99 percent of the group.
Concerns over the long-term slowdown in Chinese growth have cut iron ore prices by about half, while coal, copper and other commodities prices have fallen by 20-40%.
White House confirms Xi Jinping's visit to Washington
Chinese President Xi Jinping will make a state visit to the United States at the end of the month, a statement from the White House on Tuesday confirmed.
Xi's first official visit to Washington will take place on September 25 and will be in response to President Barack Obama's visit to Beijing last November, the statement said.
U.S. President and First Lady Michelle Obama will host a dinner for Xi and his wife Peng Liyuan after the leaders hold bilateral talks.
"President Xi's visit will allow us to expand cooperation between the United States and China on numerous global, regional and bilateral issues of common interest, and at the same time it will allow President Obama and President Xi to discuss constructively issues where there are disagreements," the statement added.
During a visit that was first announced in February, Xi is also expected to stop by Seattle on his way to Washington to meet with numerous U.S. technology leaders before continuing toward New York City and the UN General Assembly in September.
Obama and Xi are expected to discuss a number of controversial topics, including Washington's concern over China's alleged cyber espionage and the country's increased absoluteness in the disputed waters of the South China Sea.
