Xi calls for wider opening of the economy to the world
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group on Tuesday to steer the reform.
"China should commit to attracting foreign funding and expertise and developing a policy of transparency," he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the group leading the deepening of general reform.
Supporting openness while pushing ahead with reforms will add new momentum and vitality, and create new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The management team adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list of market access restrictions, relaxation of border control principles, urging state-owned companies to seize private capital, and revision of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list is created, identifying the sectors and companies in which investments are not allowed.
The system is gradually being tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant as it gives the market a greater role in resource allocation, ensures a law-based business environment, and makes the market more transparent.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to run their businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation, as well as new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
In order to open government-controlled sectors to private financiers, more sectors will open up.
"The government will not change its policy on foreign investment, and it will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, the application process for foreign permanent resident permits, "green cards", is facilitated by optimizing the requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also discussed guaranteeing the professional practice rights of lawyers and supporting professional judges and prosecutors.
Prime Minister Li Keqiang, as well as senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, also attended the meeting, according to a statement released after the meeting.
